<div id="review_4121017842" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4121017842" />
    <a title="J.K. Grice" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/72137025-j-k-grice"><img alt="J.K. Grice" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1507324623p2/72137025.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4121017842?book_show_action=true">Aug 07, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="J.K. Grice" class="user" itemprop="url" name="J.K. Grice" href="/user/show/72137025-j-k-grice">J.K. Grice</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/72137025-j-k-grice?shelf=dark-fantasy">dark-fantasy</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4121017842" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7513820900006507306">I discovered the wonderful world of the artist and writer Brom several years ago when I bought his amazing, <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/13505670.Krampus_The_Yule_Lord' title='Krampus The Yule Lord by Brom' rel='nofollow noopener'>Krampus: The Yule Lord</a>. I was blown away by Brom&apos;s evocative and beautiful artistic skills. He paints gorgeous renditions of his novel characters to enhance the dark fantasy tales he spins. His work echoes color and tone influences from the great fantasy painters, Boris Vallejo and Frank Frazetta. Brom&apos;s books are always a treat, if nothing more than to behold the incredible illustrations.</span>
  <span id="freeText7513820900006507306" style="display:none">I discovered the wonderful world of the artist and writer Brom several years ago when I bought his amazing, <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/13505670.Krampus_The_Yule_Lord" title="Krampus The Yule Lord by Brom" rel="nofollow noopener">Krampus: The Yule Lord</a>. I was blown away by Brom's evocative and beautiful artistic skills. He paints gorgeous renditions of his novel characters to enhance the dark fantasy tales he spins. His work echoes color and tone influences from the great fantasy painters, Boris Vallejo and Frank Frazetta. Brom's books are always a treat, if nothing more than to behold the incredible illustrations. <br /><br />THE CHILD THIEF is Brom's dark fantasy adaptation of the classic Barrie story, Peter Pan. And in this book, Brom adds a great deal more detail and blows the Disney concept of Peter out of the water. <br /><br />WHAT I LIKED: <br />I have already mentioned the artwork in Brom's books, and his illustrations and color plates were again stunning here. I particularly liked the relationship of his characters and settings to those of Celtic, English, and Welsh myth. I loved the darkness and horror of this novel and its underlying themes of survival, devotion, betrayal, deception, and loyalty. The characters of Peter, Nick, and the Captain were greatly nuanced with individual histories and expressions of their inner thoughts &amp; emotions. The concept of this fable was very strong &amp; original, and there were chapters in the book that were truly riveting.<br /><br />WHAT I DISLIKED:<br />I am by no means a prudish reader, but I felt there was an overuse of the word FUCK in this book. I think it detracted from the depth of a few characters and even found myself wincing at passages where the word was repeated again and again. And yes, I get it... tough street kids are going to favor high profanity, but I still feel it was overdone and Brom could have had a much more compelling story with better dialog choices. <br /><br />The second thing I think detracted from the strength of this novel was the length. At 476 pages, this tale could have easily been cleaned up and told more efficiently in a hundred or so less pages. We are told about countless bloody and gory fights and skirmishes, with characters traveling in various directions continually, and that seemed a bit repetitive to me, bogging down interest and pacing. I also thought that while we were given a few rich character backgrounds, other characters suffered because of a lack of depth and over time they felt flat to me. <br /><br />All-in-all, I'm glad I read THE CHILD THIEF, but it is not a book I would revisit.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7513820900006507306" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


